The `hashCode` method computes a hash code for a Material instance based on its attributes like mass damage, hardness damage, durability, swing speed, and texture roughness. Here is the relevant code example:

```zig
pub fn hashCode(self: Material) u32 {
	var hash: u32 = 0;
	hash = 101*%hash +% @as(u32, @bitCast(self.massDamage));
	hash = 101*%hash +% @as(u32, @bitCast(self.hardnessDamage));
	hash = 101*%hash +% @as(u32, @bitCast(self.durability));
	hash = 101*%hash +% @as(u32, @bitCast(self.swingSpeed));
	hash = 101*%hash +% @as(u32, @bitCast(self.textureRoughness));
	hash ^= hash >> 24;
	return hash;
}
```

The `initThreadLocals` function initializes the thread-local variables by setting up a stack allocator and adding the current thread to garbage collection. Here is the relevant code example:

```zig
pub fn initThreadLocals() void {
	seed = @bitCast(@as(i64, @truncate(timestamp().nanoseconds)));
	stackAllocatorBase = heap.StackAllocator.init(globalAllocator, 1 << 23);
	stackAllocator = stackAllocatorBase.allocator();
	heap.GarbageCollection.addThread();
}
```

The `characterType` function determines whether a character is a literal, symbol, or whitespace. This classification helps in managing word-based cursor movements and text selection.

```zig
fn characterType(char: u8) enum { literal, symbol, whitespace } {
	if (std.ascii.isAlphanumeric(char)) return .literal;
	if (!std.ascii.isAscii(char)) return .literal;
	if (char == '_') return .literal;
	if (std.ascii.isWhitespace(char)) return .whitespace;
	return .symbol;
}
```

The `serialize` method for the `Deposit` struct writes its destination, source, and amount to a binary writer. Here is the code example: 

```zig
fn serialize(self: Deposit, writer: *BinaryWriter) void {
	self.dest.write(writer);
	self.source.write(writer);
	writer.writeInt(u16, self.amount);
}
